name: ⌗ChrisMessina
tweet: @bjtitus Good points. I have that concern as well...  But I continue to ask: is the goal perfection and zero risk of harm?  We're seeing an analogous case with the J&J vaccine: caution is prudent but eliminating all risk negates all the upside benefits.

name: ⌗ChrisMessina
tweet: @bjtitus The video was hard to follow, TBH. Nor am I suggesting that Autopilot is perfect — far from it. But maybe that's because I presume that's imperfect rather than flawless, and so I'm not willing to hand over my life entirely to it.

name: ⌗ChrisMessina
tweet: @bjtitus I mean, remember this? People driving around in thousands of pounds of metal is the problem.   Put everyone back on bicycles and we'll all be much safer.   https://t.co/VX0aZOyAZq

name: ⌗ChrisMessina
tweet: @bjtitus This is demonstrating a completely different issue — which is the accuracy of maps data or municipalities not doing their jobs.  Yes, Teslas will get speed limit data from reading signs, but I imagine it also falls back to GPS/mapping data. If it's wrong — who's responsible?

name: ⌗ChrisMessina
tweet: @bjtitus That video is from 6 years ago. A lot has changed since then.

name: ⌗ChrisMessina
tweet: @bjtitus I'll always support finding methods to increase safety, but I have a hard time with takes that don't consider the *EXISTING* safety measures that seem, on the whole, to be largely effective.  Product designers should not be responsible for curing stupidity.
